00:06:03,320 --> 00:06:05,780
 and they go onto the highway.

121
00:06:05,780 --> 00:06:09,080
 Guys, 70 miles an hour, I'm tied in the back,

122
00:06:09,080 --> 00:06:12,840
 rolling around, just going, "Oh, Scott, where are you?"

123
00:06:12,840 --> 00:06:17,020
 You know, and finally they pull into a parking lot.

124
00:06:17,020 --> 00:06:20,400
 They drag me out of the car into this establishment.

125
00:06:20,400 --> 00:06:22,900
 They sit me down, they rip off the blindfold

126
00:06:22,900 --> 00:06:27,480
 and right in front of me is a girl holding a sign

127
00:06:27,480 --> 00:06:30,080
 saying, "Will you go to Sadie Hawkins dance with me?"

128
00:06:30,080 --> 00:06:32,120
 (congregation laughing)

129
00:06:32,120 --> 00:06:35,580
 And I'm like, "What, are you kidding me?"

130
00:06:36,600 --> 00:06:41,280
 She thought it would be cute and fun to recruit my friends

131
00:06:41,280 --> 00:06:44,480
 to kidnap me so she could ask me to the dance.

132
00:06:44,480 --> 00:06:47,680
 Now, why do I tell you all of that?

133
00:06:47,680 --> 00:06:50,840
 Because here's the reality.

134
00:06:50,840 --> 00:06:54,320
 Right now, we're in a series called 20/20

135
00:06:54,320 --> 00:06:56,760
 where we are looking at mental health

136
00:06:56,760 --> 00:07:01,760
 from the perspective of God and from His word as creator.

137
00:07:01,760 --> 00:07:06,400
 And tonight we're talking about fear and anxiety.

138
00:07:07,400 --> 00:07:09,360
 Now, here's what I know.

139
00:07:09,360 --> 00:07:11,160
 Even when I say those kinds of terms,

140
00:07:11,160 --> 00:07:14,280
 so many of us have in our mind different things

141
00:07:14,280 --> 00:07:17,640
 that come up when we think about fear

142
00:07:17,640 --> 00:07:19,680
 and when we think about anxiety.

143
00:07:19,680 --> 00:07:22,160
 But I wanna get to this book.

144
00:07:22,160 --> 00:07:26,520
 What, God, what do you say about fear and anxiety?

145
00:07:26,520 --> 00:07:27,960
 So if you have your Bible,

146
00:07:27,960 --> 00:07:31,000
 go ahead and open your Bible to the book of Psalms.

147
00:07:31,000 --> 00:07:34,240
 We're in Psalm 46 today.

148
00:07:34,240 --> 00:07:36,520
 Psalm 46, as you're turning there,

149
00:07:36,520 --> 00:07:38,560
 I just wanna do a little,

150
00:07:38,560 --> 00:07:42,600
 kinda get all on the same page of what anxiety is.

151
00:07:42,600 --> 00:07:44,840
 'Cause again, we use that term,

152
00:07:44,840 --> 00:07:47,440
 but we don't always know what it means.

153
00:07:47,440 --> 00:07:51,760
 So anxiety is actually an emotion that's similar to fear,

154
00:07:51,760 --> 00:07:53,360
 but it's not the same.

155
00:07:53,360 --> 00:07:58,360
 Fear is the response to an immediate specific threat.

156
00:07:58,360 --> 00:08:01,700
 You walk out into the woods, you see a snake,

157
00:08:01,700 --> 00:08:04,560
 and you go, "There's a snake," and that's fear.

158
00:08:04,560 --> 00:08:06,840
 Anxiety though, is the response

159
00:08:06,840 --> 00:08:10,720
 to a possible or anticipated threat.

160
00:08:10,720 --> 00:08:12,600
 You walk out into the woods and you go,

161
00:08:12,600 --> 00:08:14,840
 "There could be a snake in here," right?

162
00:08:14,840 --> 00:08:15,880
 That's anxiety.

163
00:08:15,880 --> 00:08:19,520
 Anxiety is looking into the future

164
00:08:19,520 --> 00:08:22,560
 and perceiving a possible threat.

165
00:08:22,560 --> 00:08:27,080
 And both of these are actually inherently good things.

166
00:08:27,080 --> 00:08:29,640
 Like they've been hardwired into us

167
00:08:29,640 --> 00:08:34,640
 as a survival method in order to survive, to not die.

168
00:08:34,640 --> 00:08:36,700
 That both fear and anxiety,

169
00:08:36,700 --> 00:08:38,920
 they're almost like a fire alarm.

170
00:08:38,920 --> 00:08:40,380
 Like you think about a fire alarm,

171
00:08:40,380 --> 00:08:42,880
 a fire alarm primarily exists

172
00:08:42,880 --> 00:08:46,680
 as a life saving mechanism, right?

173
00:08:46,680 --> 00:08:51,060
 And yet oftentimes a fire alarm goes off randomly

174
00:08:51,060 --> 00:08:52,640
 when there's nothing there.

175
00:08:52,640 --> 00:08:54,640
 Or the fire alarm will just keep going

176
00:08:54,640 --> 00:08:56,200
 after the fire has been put out.

177
00:08:56,200 --> 00:08:59,760
 And that's what anxiety disorder is.

178
00:08:59,760 --> 00:09:01,620
 So many times when we think about anxiety,

179
00:09:01,620 --> 00:09:03,160
 we originally think it's bad.

180
00:09:03,160 --> 00:09:05,660
 No, anxiety can be good.

181
00:09:05,660 --> 00:09:08,680
 You can be anxious about, "I have a date coming up.

182
00:09:08,680 --> 00:09:10,440
 I'm anxious, I should smell good."

183
00:09:10,440 --> 00:09:11,400
 That's good.

184
00:09:11,400 --> 00:09:13,760
 That's good anxiety, right?

185
00:09:13,760 --> 00:09:17,100
 But anxiety disorder is when the fire alarm keeps going on.

186
00:09:17,100 --> 00:09:19,480
 And that fire alarm wakes you up

187
00:09:19,480 --> 00:09:21,960
 in the middle of the night for no reason.

188
00:09:21,960 --> 00:09:24,400
 There's no smoke, there's no fire,

189
00:09:24,400 --> 00:09:28,400
 but my heart is racing, my stomach is churning,

190
00:09:28,400 --> 00:09:31,940
 and I can not make it go away.

191
00:09:31,940 --> 00:09:35,000
 And here's the reality.

192
00:09:35,000 --> 00:09:39,860
 Our culture is in a moment

193
00:09:39,860 --> 00:09:42,880
 where anxiety as a whole has skyrocketed.

194
00:09:42,880 --> 00:09:47,880
 It's interesting from 1938, it's a long time ago, to 2010,

195
00:09:47,880 --> 00:09:53,400
 there was marginally no statistical change in anxiety

196
00:09:54,400 --> 00:09:56,840
 from 1938 to 2010.

197
00:09:56,840 --> 00:10:01,840
 It was a very slight positive increase, just a little.

198
00:10:01,840 --> 00:10:07,320
 From 2010 to 2015, for the ages of 26 to 34,

199
00:10:07,320 --> 00:10:13,280
 anxiety increased by 103% in five years.

200
00:10:13,280 --> 00:10:18,280
 Marginal increase from 1938 to 2010 in five years, 100%.

201
00:10:18,920 --> 00:10:23,920
 For ages 18 to 25, it increased 139%.

202
00:10:23,920 --> 00:10:27,120
 To the degree where now, a few years ago,

203
00:10:27,120 --> 00:10:29,220
 a study was done of young adults

204
00:10:29,220 --> 00:10:33,640
 that found that 37% of young adults, over a third,

205
00:10:33,640 --> 00:10:38,640
 would say, "I always, or most of the time, feel anxious."

206
00:10:38,640 --> 00:10:40,180
 You just think about a room in here,

207
00:10:40,180 --> 00:10:43,120
 a third of you would go, "Yeah, most of the time,

208
00:10:43,120 --> 00:10:47,100
 or all the time, I'm feeling that heart racing feel."

209
00:10:47,100 --> 00:10:50,160
 Then on top of that, another 31% said

210
00:10:50,160 --> 00:10:52,640
 they feel anxious about half the time.

211
00:10:52,640 --> 00:10:58,200
 So only about a third of young adults, if they were honest,

212
00:10:58,200 --> 00:11:01,640
 would say, "I am anxious at least half the time,

213
00:11:01,640 --> 00:11:03,980
 or less, or none at all."

214
00:11:03,980 --> 00:11:08,980
 Two thirds would say, "The majority of my life, I'm anxious."

215
00:11:08,980 --> 00:11:13,360
 Now, what in the world happened in 2010

216
00:11:13,360 --> 00:11:15,520
 to make it skyrocket?

217
00:11:15,520 --> 00:11:17,620
 I read a book called "The Anxious Generation"

218
00:11:17,620 --> 00:11:19,980
 by Jonathan Haidt, some of you've heard this.

219
00:11:19,980 --> 00:11:23,420
 And Jonathan Haidt is a researcher, he's an author,

220
00:11:23,420 --> 00:11:28,420
 and he labels 2010 to 2015 as the great rewiring,

221
00:11:28,420 --> 00:11:32,740
 because two main things happened in 2010.

222
00:11:32,740 --> 00:11:34,520
 Do you know what they are?

223
00:11:34,520 --> 00:11:39,520
 The first is in 2010, the iPhone 4 came out,

224
00:11:39,520 --> 00:11:43,260
 which had a front-facing camera for the first time.

225
00:11:43,260 --> 00:11:44,400
 That's the first one.

226
00:11:44,400 --> 00:11:48,180
 Before 2010, you had to take a selfie

227
00:11:48,180 --> 00:11:51,000
 not knowing what it was gonna look like, right?

228
00:11:51,000 --> 00:11:53,820
 The second thing is social media turned

229
00:11:53,820 --> 00:11:58,100
 from primarily a networking tool to a platform

230
00:11:58,100 --> 00:11:59,660
 in the creation of Instagram.

231
00:11:59,660 --> 00:12:02,740
 You think about social media before was,

232
00:12:02,740 --> 00:12:05,300
 "Let me connect with all my friends

233
00:12:05,300 --> 00:12:06,820
 and find out where they are."

234
00:12:06,820 --> 00:12:10,500
 Instagram came and it was, "I don't care who's following me.

235
00:12:10,500 --> 00:12:12,740
 I just care that I have a following.

236
00:12:12,740 --> 00:12:15,680
 And I'm checking my likes, and I'm checking my responses,

237
00:12:15,680 --> 00:12:17,280
 and I'm creating content."

238
00:12:17,280 --> 00:12:21,040
 And it's all about a platform

239
00:12:21,040 --> 00:12:25,120
 that's elevating my online virtual life.

240
00:12:25,120 --> 00:12:29,600
 In 2010, only 23% of young adults had a smartphone.

241
00:12:29,600 --> 00:12:33,840
 Five years later in 2015, 79% had a smartphone,

242
00:12:33,840 --> 00:12:37,200
 and now 97% have a smartphone.

243
00:12:37,200 --> 00:12:40,160
 In 15 years, that's quite a change.

244
00:12:40,160 --> 00:12:42,800
 And then when it comes to social media and screen time,

245
00:12:42,800 --> 00:12:46,080
 50% of young adults say that they are online

246
00:12:46,080 --> 00:12:49,680
 almost constantly, almost constantly.

247
00:12:49,680 --> 00:12:51,640
 The average screen time of a young adult

248
00:12:51,640 --> 00:12:53,600
 is six to eight hours.

249
00:12:53,600 --> 00:12:54,500
 So I wanna do something.

250
00:12:54,500 --> 00:12:57,320
 This is risky, and I didn't run it by anybody.

251
00:12:57,320 --> 00:12:59,480
 I'm sorry, team, but we're gonna try it.

252
